    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Hey, i need some help writing an email. We have a candidate for a Senior DevOps role who made it all the way to the final round, but we decided to go with someone else. The candidate was actually really impressive—very strong on Kubernetes and AWS—so i want the rejection to be super professional and empathetic so we don't burn any bridges. Can you help me draft that?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Here are a few options for drafting that email, focusing on professionalism and empathy. You want to be clear but gentle, making sure the candidate feels respected even though they weren't chosen.\n\nHere is a draft you can adapt:\n\nSubject: Update on the Senior DevOps Role at [Company Name]\n\nDear [Candidate Name],\n\nThank you so much for taking the time to interview with our team for the Senior DevOps position. We were incredibly impressed with your depth of knowledge, particularly your expertise in Kubernetes and AWS. The final decision was extremely difficult, as the caliber of candidates was very high, and we have decided to move forward with another candidate whose specific experience was a slightly closer match to our immediate needs.\n\nWe truly value the time and effort you invested in this process, and we wish you the very best in your job search and future endeavors. Please keep in touch, as we hope our paths may cross again.\n\nBest regards,\n\n[Your Name]\n\n***\n\n*This draft is professional, acknowledges their strengths (Kubernetes/AWS), and gives a gentle reason for the decision without being overly specific. It keeps the door open for future opportunities.*\n\n*It’s important to send this relatively quickly so they aren",
